@endnode
@node USAGE "Usage"
 After program startup you need to specify two directories: source
and destination. Both source and destination are accessed in the
same way, by standard AmigaOS means, so you will need to start
AmigaNCP-Filesystem to access your Psion, then select a path on
Psion's device. Usually it will be "NCP:C" (root of Psion's internal
RAM-disk). Also you may wish to set up some @{"preferences" LINK "WINDOW_PREFS"}.
When you're done press "Start" button and just wait for the backup to be
performed. At any time you can abort the operation by pressing "Stop".
 In fact with AmigaNCP-Backup you can backup not only your Psion but any
drawer on your Amiga. But in this case will have to note the following
limitations:

 - datestamps of drawers are not preserved;
 - comments are not preserved;
 - links can be not supported. On my system AmigaNCP-Backup failed when
   processing softlink to a file, the link was interpreted as a subdirectory.
   I did not test other cases.
 
 The program has protection against incorrect situations when source (or
destination) specified is a subdirectory of destination (source). A simple
string comparing is used to do this, so the program will fail if you specify
for example "Work:MyDir" as a source and "Work:MyDir1" as destination. But in
most cases you will not notice this.
 
 For those who interested, here is detailed step-by-step description of the
backup algorythm:

1. Source and destination drawers are listed into memory;
2. Each file (drawer) in the source is compared with the same file (drawer)
   in the destination. If the file (drawer) does not exist in the destination,
   it will be copied there. Otherwise, if the object exists and it is file,
   datestamps of this file in source and destination are compared. If dates
   are different, the file will be copied from source to destination.
   Copied file is removed from the destination list in memory.
   Files and drawers are copied with their protection bits.
   NOTE: you can specify in the @{"preferences" LINK "WINDOW_PREFS"}, that files in the destination
   which have later datestamp than in source must be left as is.
3. At this point destination list will contain olny entries which do not
   exist in source. They will be deleted.
   NOTE: you can disable this step in the @{"preferences" LINK "WINDOW_PREFS"}.
@endnode
@node WINDOWS "Windows"
 There are three windows in AmigaNCP-Backup:

@{"Main               " LINK "WINDOW_MAIN"}
@{"Backup preferences " LINK "WINDOW_PREFS"}
@{"Backup log         " LINK "WINDOW_LOG"}
@endnode
@node WINDOW_MAIN "Main window"
 Main window is the window which you see after program's startup. It contains
the following elements:

 @{b}"Source:" text entry field.@{ub}
 
 Here you should enter a drawer which you wish to backup. Usually it will
be "NCP:C/" (root of your Psion's internal RAM disk), but you may wish to
perform a partial backup, and select a subdirectory here. You can enter the
text into a field or press button to the left of it to bring up a standard
AmigaOS drawer requester window.

 @{b}"Destination:" text entry field.@{ub}
 
 Here you should enter a drawer where to place the backup copy. No additional
drawers will be created inside it, so be careful. Backup procedure will
likely erase everything inside this drawer.

 @{b}Progress bars.@{ub}
 
 These nice green LED indicators will inform you about progress of the backup
procedure. Upper indicator shows overall progress of the operation, lower one
shows copying a single file.

 @{b}Status line.@{ub}
 
 It will show what's happening in the text form. It can say that the program
is examining drawers in order to collect information about files, or show
name of the file (or drawer) which is being currently processed.

 @{b}"Start" button.@{ub}
 
 To start the backup process, press this button. During the backup process it
will be disabled.

 @{b}"Stop" button.@{ub}
 
 This button is enabled only when backup process runs. You can press it at any
time to abort the process. Note that file copying operation will not be
finished, and current file will not be copied at all.

 Closing the window (quitting the program) while backup process is running
will terminate it too. But in this case you'll see a warning requester window,
where you can accept or discard your wish.
@endnode
@node WINDOW_PREFS "Preferences window"
 From this window you can set some backup modes. The program can not only do
"Blind" backup, but includes two options which i thought may be useful in
some special cases (especially for "advanced" people).

 @{b}"Modified files" radio buttons.@{ub}
 
 These buttons allows you to specify what program should do if the file in
source has earlier date than in destination. You can choose from two options:

 Replace - replace the file in destination with the file from source.
 Leave   - leave the file in destination as is. This allows you to make some
           modifications to an already-made backup.

 @{b}"Deleted files" radio buttons.
@{ub}
 These button specify what program should do with files (or drawers) that do
not exist in source, but exist in destination. Such files (drawers) are
considered to be old and deleted from the source. There are two options:

 Delete - delete the file(or drawer) from destination too.
 Leave  - leave the file in destination as is. This can be useful if you for
          example had some project on your Psion, then finished and deleted
          it, but still wish to be able to recover it from the backup.

 @{b}"Remember directories on exit" checkmark.

@{ub} It you turn on this option, the program will remember the drawers you
entered in "Source:" and "Destination:" fields automatically when you exit
it.

 @{b}"Save" button.
@{ub}
 Accepts your preferences and saves it to a program's configuration file.
 
 @{b}"Use" button.@{ub}
 
 Accepts your preferences for current session, but does not save them. On
next program startup you will get previous settings.

 @{b}"Cancel" button.@{ub}
 
 Just closes the preferences window discarding all changes. The same thing
occurs if you hit window close button.

 Main window is disabled while the preferences window is open.
@endnode
@node WINDOW_LOG "Log window"
 In this window you can see details of the backup process. It contains a list
divided into three columns: "Type","Name" and "Action". "Type" field shows
whether an item is a file or directory. "Name" contains relative (to the
source or destination - this does not matter) path to the item, and "Action"
can be of:

 Skipped - a file (or drawer) skipped because the same file with the same date
           (or drawer with the same name) already exists in the destination
           (it is already backed-up and up-to-date).
 Copied  - a file was copied from source to destination (file or drawer did
           not exist in destination, or file existed but it had another date).
 Deleted - a file (or drawer) deleted from the destination because it did not
           exist in source. You will not see such messages in the log if you
           disabled deleting old files in the @{"preferences window" LINK "WINDOW_PREFS"}.
           
 Log is cleared every time when you start a new backup operation.
@endnode
@node MENUS "Menus"
 There are following menus in the AmigaNCP-Backup:
 
 @{b}"Program" menu.@{ub}
 
   View log     - open the log window.
   Help         - bring up online help (this document).
   About...     - display information about AmigaNCP-Backup's version and
                  copyright.
   About MUI... - display information about MUI user interface library.
   Quit         - Quit program (the same as hitting close button of main
                  window).

 @{b}"Settings" menu.@{ub}

   Program settings... - open the @{"preferences window" LINK "WINDOW_PREFS"}. This menu item is
                         disabled while backup process is running.
   MUI settings...     - open the standard MUI user interface settings
                         window.
   Save derectories    - remember directories entered in "Source" and
                         "Destination" fields. They will appear there on
                         each program startup.
@endnode
